INTRODUCTION Return to Table of Contents
Petitioner David Whitaker was the defendant in the trial court and will be referred to by name.
Respondent, State of Colorado, will be referred to as the prosecution or the State.
Numbers in parentheses refer to the volume and page number of the record on appeal.
ISSUES ANNOUNCED BY THE COURT Return to Table of Contents
I. Whether the district court erroneously instructed the jury regarding the elements of the crime of possession of one thousand grams or more of a controlled substance with intent to distribute, and if the court of appeals erroneously concluded that the prosecution was not required to prove that petitioner knowingly possessed such amount to trigger an enhanced sentence?
II.
Whether the district court erroneously treated petitioner's special offender charge as a "sentence enhancer" rather than as a substantive offense or as an element of the possession with the intent to distribute charge, and if the court of appeals incorrectly relied on People v. Ramirez to determine that the prosecution need not prove mens rea with respect to that charge?
STATEMENT OF THE CASE Return to Table of Contents
On January 21, 1998, the district attorney filed an information in the Mesa County district court charging Mr. Whitaker with importation of a schedule II controlled substance[1], possession of over one thousand grams of a schedule II controlled substance with intent to distribute[2]
Mr. Whitaker was tried at a jury trial on the charges of possession of over a thousand grams of a schedule II controlled substance with intent to distribute and introduction, distribution or importation of a schedule II controlled substance and found guilty.(v1,p84) The charges of possession of a schedule II controlled substance with intent to distribute and possession of drug paraphernalia were dismissed by the prosecutor.(PSIR,p1; minute order 8/18/98) On September 30, 1998, the district court sentenced Mr. Whitaker to 20 years in the state prison.(v5,p70) On November 16, 1998, Mr. Whitaker filed a notice of appeal in the Court of Appeals, thereby perfecting his right to appeal.(flat file) On September 14, 2000, the Court of Appeals issued an opinion affirming Mr. Whitaker's conviction and sentence.
(flat file)
STATEMENT OF THE FACTS Return to Table of Contents
On January 14, 1998, Grand Junction Police Department officers boarded a Denver-bound Greyhound bus as part of a "narcotics and weapons interdiction program."(v4,p140) At the Grand Junction bus depot, all passengers were "off-loaded", the bus was serviced and then the passengers re-boarded the bus.(v4,p141) At this point, three police officers boarded the bus, identified themselves as law enforcement and informed the passengers that they were going to talk to each and every passenger, if that was all right with them.(v4,p142) One officer remained near the door at the front of the bus while the other two officers went to the rear of the bus and talked to passengers.(v4,p141-142)
During this procedure, the officers talked to David Whitaker.(v4,p145) The officers testified that Mr. Whitaker was nervous while speaking to the officers.(v4,p144-145) Mr. Whitaker, responding to questions from the officers, indicated that he did not have any bags on the bus.(v4,p146) Officers pointed to a black bag near Mr. Whitaker and asked if that was his luggage.(v4,p150) Mr. Whitaker indicated that it was not his bag, but that he had put some of his things in the bag because it did not appear that anyone was using it.(v4,p172-174) Officers searched the bag and found several duct tape covered packages in the bottom of the bag.(v4,p180) The officers cut open the packages and found a substance later identified as methamphetamine.(v4,p184)
At trial, Mr. Whitaker continued to maintain that although he had put a few small items into the bag, the packages of drugs were not his and he did not know that they were in the bag.(v4, p133-135)
ARGUMENT
I. Conviction and sentencing for possession of over one thousand grams of a controlled substance under C.R.S. รยง 18-18-405 requires proof beyond a reasonable doubt and a jury finding that the defendant knew he possessed over one thousand grams of the controlled substance.
Return to Table of Contents
The district court erroneously instructed the jury regarding the elements of possession of one thousand grams or more of a controlled substance with the intent to distribute.
The elemental instruction failed to convey that the mens rea of knowingly applied to all elements of the crime, including possession of over one thousand grams.
This error violated Mr. Whitaker's right to jury trial and due process rights because the jury was not required to find that he acted with the requisite culpable mental state with respect to the quantity of controlled substance.
A.
The District Court's Jury Instruction Return to Table of Contents
The district court instructed the jurors in instruction number 11:
The elements of the crime of Possession of 1000 Grams or More of a Controlled Substance with Intent to Distribute are:
1.
That the defendant,
2.
in the State of Colorado, at or about the date and place charged,
3.
knowingly or intentionally,
4.
possessed with intent to distribute with or without remuneration,
5.
the controlled substance methamphetamine,
6.
and the controlled substance possessed by the defendant weighed one thousand grams or more.
. . .
(v1,p80) (emphasis added) Defense counsel did not object to the instruction.
B. Argument.
1.
Section 18-18-405 and COLJI acknowledge drug quantity as elemental to the crime of possession with intent to distribute, and the requisite mental state applies to it Return to Table of Contents
Section 18-1-503(4) provides:
When a statute defining an offense prescribes as an element thereof a specified culpable mental state, that mental state is deemed to apply to every element of the offense unless an intent to limit its application clearly appears.
(emphasis added).
The district court's instruction is incorrect.
It does not require the jury to find that Mr. Whitaker knowingly possessed over one thousand grams of a schedule II controlled substance.
It separates the element defining the quantity of controlled substance from the mens rea element.
It deviates from the pattern COLJI instruction because it includes the word "and" before the sixth element and therefore does not require the jury to find that Mr. Whitaker knowingly possessed a controlled substance weighing over one thousand grams.
This offense is defined in section 18-18-405, 6 C.R.S. (1998) as follows:
(1)(a). . .
it is unlawful for any person knowingly . . . possess with intent to . . . distribute a controlled substance.
. .
. . .
(2) . . . any person who violates any of the provisions of subsection (1) of this section:
(a) In the case of a controlled substance listed in schedule I or II of part 2 of this article, commits:
(I) A class 3 felony; except that a person commits a class 4 felony if such violation is based on the possession of a controlled substance listed in schedule II unless otherwise provided in paragraph (a) of subsection (3) of this section;
. . .
(3)(a) Except as otherwise provided in section 18-18-407 relating to special offenders, any person convicted pursuant to paragraph (a) of subsection (2) of this section for knowingly . . . possessing with intent to . . . distribute . . .
an amount that is or has been represented to be:
. . .
(III) One thousand grams or one kilogram or more of any material compound, mixture, or preparation that contains a schedule I or schedule II controlled substance as listed in section 18-18-203 or 18-18-204 shall be sentenced to the department of correction for a term greater than the maximum presumptive range but not more than twice the maximum presumptive range provided for such offense in section 18-1-105(1)(a).
The Colorado pattern jury instructions do not include a jury instruction for the statute in its current form, but they do contain a model instruction for the similarly constructed precursor to this statute:
36:16 AGGRAVATED DISTRIBUTING, MANUFACTURING, DISPENSING, SELLING, POSSESSING COCAINE
The elements of the crime of aggravated [distribution] [manufacturing]
1.
